<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="notes-china">
  <title>Ancient Chinese Mathematics (5.3, 5.5)</title>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-The-Nine-Chapters">
    <title>The Nine Chapters</title>

    <p>
        With thousands of years of continuous civilization, China is one of the world's oldest cultures. Chinese history can be divided into 3 broad periods: Ancient (8500 - 221 B.C.), Imperial (221 B.C. - 1912 A.D) and modern (1912- ). Many different dynasties have rule over parts of China over the years. Some of the most important ones are the Shang (1600-1046 B.C.), Han (202 B.C. - 220 A.D.), Tang (618 - 906 A.D.), Song (960 - 1279 A.D.), and Yuan (1279-1368 A.D.).
    </p>

    <p>
        Chinese culture and thought was hugely influential in East Asia, much the same way that Greek culture influenced Europe. Mathematics was one of the six arts of Ancient China. Mastery of all six was required to be a <term>Junzi</term> or respectable person. Because of vast geographical distances, Chinese mathematics developed independently from Babylonian, Egyptian, and Greek mathematics. Certain results, like the Pythagorean Theorem were developed independently in both cultures.
    </p>

    <p>
       The most influential work of Ancient Chinese Mathematics is <em>The Nine Chapters on the Mathematical Art</em> or <em>The Nine Chapters</em> for short, which can be compared with Euclid's <em>Elements</em>. Unlike <em>The Elements</em> we do not know who wrote <em>The Nine Chapters</em> and likely it was compiled by multiple scholars over several generations from the 10th century to 2nd century BC. Because it is referenced by other Chinese sources, we know that it had to been written prior to 93 A.D.   
    </p>

    <p>
      Much like <em>The Elements</em>,  <em>The Nine Chapters</em> consists of a series of problems, followed by the solution and an explanation of the procedure that led to the solution. In all there are 246 problems in <em>The Nine Chapters</em>
    </p>
    
<p>
    Liu Hui, who used the method of exhaustion to determine the most accurate estimate of <m>\pi</m> at the time wrote a commentary on <em>The Nine Chapters</em> in 263, explaining the procedures in more detail as well as providing explanations for why the procedure yields the correct solution.  
</p>

<p>
  <em>The Nine Chapters</em> is divided into nine chapters that cover a variety of mathematical topics.
</p>

<p>
  Chapter 1 is called <term>Fangtian (Bounding Fields)</term>. It includes formulas for areas of various shapes such as triangles, rectangles, trapezoids, and circles. It also includes rules for counting rod manipulation. Liu Hui's commentary for this section includes his method for calculating <m>\pi</m> and his approximate value of <m>3.14159</m>
</p>

<p>
  Chapter 2 is called <term>Sumi (Millet and Rice)</term>. It involves the exchange of commodities at different rates, solving proportions and using fractions. 
</p>

<p>
  Chapter 3 is called <term>Cuifen (Proportional Distribution)</term>. It involves distribution of money and commodities at proportional rates as well as arithmetic and geometric sums.
</p>

<p>
  As an example, Chapter 3 Problem 3 states
</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>
    There is a woman weaver who increases an [equal] amount each day. She weaves <m>5</m> chi on the first day and in a month <m>9</m> pi <m>3</m> zang. Find her increase each day.
  </p>
</blockquote>

<p>
  Chapter 4 is called <term>Shaoguang (Reducing Dimensions)</term>. It involves finding the diameter or side length of a shape given its area or volume and extractions of square roots and cube roots.
</p>

<p>
  Problem 12 of this chapter states
</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>
    One has a square area of <m>55,225</m> pu. What is the side of the square?
  </p>
</blockquote>

<p>
  The answer is <m>\sqrt{55,255}</m> but the problem is to find the exact value. In <em>The Nine Chapters</em> this is done using the algebraic identity
  <md>
    (a+b+c)^2 = a^2+(2a+b)b + [2(a+b)+c]c
  </md>
  
</p>

<p>
  To extract the square root of <m>55,255</m> using the above identity one dissects a square of area <m>N = 55,225</m> as follows. This method can be used to extract the square root for any <m>N</m>
</p>

<p>
  Because <m>100^2 = 10,000 &lt; 55,255 &lt; 1,000,000 = 1,000^3</m> it follows that <m>\sqrt{N} = d_1d_2d_3</m>, i.e. a 3 digit number.
</p>

<p>
  To obtain the first digit <m>d_1</m> one seeks the largest square of side <m>S_1 = d_1 \cdot 10^2</m> satisfying <m>S_1^2 \leq N = 55,255</m>. Since <m>200^2 = 40,000 &lt; 90,000 = 300^2</m>, it follows that <m>d_1 = 2</m> 
</p>

<p>
  Removing the square with area <m>S_1^2</m> from the square of area <m>N</m> leaves a region with area <m>15,255</m>. The second digit <m>d_2</m> is found by selecting the largest value <m>S_2 = d_2 \cdot 10^1</m> with the property that
  <md>
    2S_1S_2+S_2^2 \leq N-S_1^2 = 15255
  </md>
  
</p>

<p>
  Before finding <m>d_2</m> let us explain the rationale for this condition. <m>2S_1S_2+s_2^2</m> is the area of two rectangles with sides <m>S_1</m> and <m>S_2</m> plus a square with side <m>S_2</m>. Adding this to the square of side <m>S_1</m> that we previously removed and together we have removed a square with side <m>S_1+S_2</m> from our original square with area <m>N</m>.
</p>


<figure>
      <caption>The rectangle used to extract the square root.</caption>
      <image source="root_extraction.png" width="50%">
        <description>Diagram of a large square subdivided into regions based on three side lengths labeled S1, S2, and S3. Along the top edge, the width is partitioned into three vertical strips: a wide strip labeled S1 on the left, a narrower strip labeled S2 in the middle, and a very narrow strip labeled S3 on the right. Along the left edge, the height is similarly partitioned into three horizontal strips: a tall section labeled S1 at the top, a shorter section labeled S2 in the middle, and a thin section labeled S3 at the bottom.
The partition lines form a grid of rectangular regions. The upper-left region is a large square of side length S1. To its right are two vertical rectangles with widths S2 and S3 and height S1. Below the large S1 square are two horizontal rectangles with height S2 and S3 and width S1. At the intersection of the S2 row and S2 column is a square of side length S2. Additional small rectangles occupy the remaining regions where the S2 and S3 strips intersect. The diagram visually represents the decomposition of a square with side length S1 + S2 + S3 into smaller squares and rectangles determined by the lengths S1, S2, and S3.
</description>
      </image>
    </figure>



<p>
  To solve for <m>d_2</m> we notice that <m>2\cdot200\cdot 30 + 30^2 = 12,900</m> and <m>2\cdot200\cdot 40 + 40^2 = 17,600</m>. Thus <m>d_2 = 3</m>. Removing this area from the original square leaves an area of <m>2325</m>
</p>

<p>
  The third digit <m>d_3</m> is found by finding the largest value <m>S_3 = d_3 \cdot 10^0</m> for which
  <md>
    2(S_1+S_2)S_3 + S_3^2 \leq 2325.
  </md>
  
</p>

<p>
  The rationale for this choice is that <m>2(S_1+S_2)S_3 + S_3^2</m> is the area of two rectangles with sides <m>S_1+S_2</m> and <m>S_3</m> plus a square with side <m>S_3</m>. When added to the regions that were already removed, the total amount removed is a square with side length <m>S_1+S_2+S_3</m> proving the identity at the start of this problem.
</p>

<p>
  Note that <m>2(200+30)5+5^2 = 2325</m> exactly. Thus <m>d_3=5</m> and the square root of <m>55225</m> is <m>235</m>.
</p>

<p>
  Square root extraction doesn't result in a whole number answer unless you start with a perfect square. When this wasn't the case this method could be continued to produce a series of decimal places.
</p>

<p>
  Chapter 5 is called <term>Shanggong (Figuring for Construction)</term>. It covers finding volumes of solids of various shapes including pyramids, prisms, and cones.
</p>

<p>
  Chapter 6 is called <term>Junshu (Equitable Taxation)</term>. It covers problems on proportion, work, distances, and rates. As an example, Problem 26 in this section is one of my favorites: 
</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>
    A cistern is filled through five canals. Open the first canal and the cistern fills in <m>\frac{1}{3}</m> day; with the second, it fills in <m>1</m> day; with the third, in <m>2\frac{1}{2}</m>; with the fourth, in <m>3</m> days, and with the fifth in <m>5</m> days. If all the canals are opened how long will it take to fill the cistern?
  </p>
</blockquote>

<p>
  The solution is to reframe the problem by considering what portion of the cistern does each canal fill in a day. The first canal can fill <m>3</m> cisterns in a day, the second can fill <m>1</m>, the third can fill <m>\frac{2}{5}</m>, the fourth <m>\frac{1}{3}</m> and the fifth <m>\frac{1}{5}</m>. Adding them altogether we see that in one day all five canals can fill <m>\frac{74}{15}</m> cisterns in a day. Thus it would take <m>\frac{15}{74}</m> of a day to fill one cistern. 
</p>

<p>
  Chapter 7 is called <term>Yingbuzu (Excess and Deficit)</term>. It covers linear problems that are solved using the method of false position.
</p>

<p>
  Chapter 8 is called <term>Fangcheng (Rectangular Arrays)</term>. It covers systems of linear equations which is solved using the method of Gaussian elimination (1600 years before Gauss!). We will cover this method in a later section.
</p>

<p>
  Chapter 9 is called <term>Gougu (Base and Altitude)</term>. It covers problems involving right triangles that are solved with the Pythagorean Theorem. These problems demonstrate that the Pythagorean theorem was independently discovered by Chinese mathematicians. The <term>Gougu</term> rule states:
</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>
    Add the squares of the <term>gou</term> [short leg] and the <term>gu</term> [long leg], take the square root [of the sum] giving the hypotenuse. Further the square of the gu is subtracted from the square of the hypotenuse. The square root of the remainder is the gou. Further, the square of the gou is subtracted from the square on the hypotenuse. The square root of the remainder is the gu.
  </p>
</blockquote>

<figure>
      <caption>A historic Chinese illustration of the Pythagorean Theorem. (Public Domain, https://commons.wikimedia.org/w/index.php?curid=104738)</caption>
      <image source="Chinese_pythagoras.jpg" width="50%">
        <description>Historical Chinese mathematical diagram drawn on a square grid. A large diamond (a square rotated 45 degrees) is inscribed within the grid, with its four vertices touching the midpoint regions of the top, right, bottom, and left sides of the outer square. Thick dark lines outline the diamond and form a vertical and horizontal cross through its center, dividing the interior into several geometric regions.
Multiple Chinese labels appear inside and around the figure. Most regions are labeled “朱鬻” (red millet), while a small central square formed by the intersecting cross is labeled “黃實” (yellow square). Additional vertical Chinese text runs down the left side of the image outside the grid.
The diagram is black and white and resembles a page from an ancient Chinese mathematics text. The geometric construction visually partitions the inscribed diamond into smaller areas, likely illustrating a proof or geometric relationship involving areas, such as the Pythagorean theorem.
</description>
      </image>
    </figure>

<p>
  Questions to consider: <ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        What are some similarities between <em>The Elements</em> and <em>The Nine Chapters</em>?
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        What kinds of mathematics are emphasized more in <em>The Elements</em> than in <em>The Nine Chapters</em>?
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        What kinds of mathematics are emphasized more in <em>The Nine Chapters</em> than in <em>The Elements</em>?
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol>
</p>




    
  </subsection>


  <subsection xml:id="subsec-Chinese-remainder-theorem">
    <title>The Chinese Remainder Theorem</title>



    <p>
      The following problem appears in the book <em>Sunzi Suan Jing</em> (The Mathematical Classic of Master Sun) from around the 5th century A.D.
    </p>

    <blockquote>
      <p>
        Suppose we have an unknown number of objects. If they are counted in threes, <m>2</m> are left, if they are counted in fives, <m>3</m> are left and if they are counted in sevens, <m>2</m> are left. How many objects are there?
      </p>
    </blockquote>

    <p>
      These types of problems are known as the <term>Chinese Remainder Theorem</term> and were also considered by the Medieval Italian mathematician Leonardo of Pisa (Fibonacci) and Medieval Arabic mathematician ibn al-Haytham.
    </p>

    <p>
      Sunzi gives <m>23</m> as the answer to his problem and his solution is as follows:
    </p>

    <blockquote>
      <p>
        If they are counted in threes, <m>2</m> are left: set <m>140</m>. If they are counted in fives, <m>3</m> are left: set <m>63</m>. If they are counted in sevens: <m>2</m> are left: set <m>30</m>. Take the sum of these [three numbers] to obtain <m>233</m>. Subtract <m>210</m> from this total; this gives the answer.
      </p>

      <p>
        In general: For each remaining unit when counting in threes, set <m>70</m>. For each remaining unit when counting in fives, set <m>21</m>. For each remaining unit when counting in sevens, set <m>15</m>. If [the sum obtained in this way] is <m>106</m> or more, subtract <m>105</m> to obtain the answer.
      </p>

    </blockquote>

    <p>
      Question: Where do you suppose the numbers <m>70, 21, 15,</m> and <m>105</m> come from? 
    </p>

    <p>
      Sunzi's rule can be generalized to solve the following problem:
    </p>

    <p>
      If they are counted in <m>a</m>s, <m>r</m> are left, if they are counted in <m>b</m>s, <m>s</m> are left and if they are counted in <m>c</m>s, <m>t</m> are left. How many objects are there?
    </p>

    <p>
      Sunzi's rule for this problem is as follows. When counting in <m>a</m>s, set <m>bcR</m> where <m>R</m> will be determined shortly. When counting in <m>b</m>s set <m>acS</m> and when counting in <m>c</m>s set <m>abT</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Consider the sum <m>bcRr + acSs + abTt</m> and subtract from this the largest multiple of <m>abc</m> that is less than it, say <m>nabc</m>. This gives the correct solution.
    </p>

    <p>
      Now let's consider why this process leads to the correct answer. Note that when divided by <m>a</m> the number <m>bcRr + acSs + abTt</m> has the same remainder as <m>bcRr</m> because both <m>acSs</m> and <m>abTt</m> are divisible by <m>a</m>. So the number <m>bcRr</m> and the number we want give the same remainder when dividing by <m>a</m> and for this we find a small number <m>R</m> such that <m>bcR</m> has a remainder of <m>1</m> when divided by <m>a</m>. In Sunzi's problem <m>a=3</m>, <m>b=5</m> and <m>c=7</m> we find that <m>bc=35</m> which has a remainder of <m>2</m> when divided by <m>3</m>. However, <m>70</m> has a remainder of <m>1</m> when divided by <m>3</m> which is why Sunzi used <m>70</m> instead of <m>35</m> in his solution. 
    </p>

    <p>
      Similarly when divided by <m>b</m>, <m>bcRr + acSs + abTt</m> has the same remainder as <m>acSs</m> and when divided by <m>c</m>, <m>bcRr + acSs + abTt</m> has the same remainder as <m>abTt</m>. By repeating the above process we can select numbers so that the sum will have the desired remainders for each division.
    </p>

    <p>
      Finally because <m>abc</m> has remainder <m>0</m> when divided by <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, or <m>c</m>, subtracting multiples of it doesn't change the divisibility. In fact we can add or subtract a multiple of <m>abc</m> to a solution to get another solution. In Sunzi's problem <m>abc = 105</m> and adding <m>105</m> to <m>23</m> gives <m>128</m> which also solves the problem. Typically the smallest positive number is sought as the solution to Chinese Remainder Theorem problems.
    </p>

    <p>
      Example: There is an unknown number of objects: When counted in threes, the remainder is <m>1</m>; when counted in sevens, the remainder is <m>5</m>; when counted in elevens, the remainder is <m>6</m>. How many objects are there?
    </p>

    
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-Counting-Boards">
    <title>Counting Boards and Systems of Equations</title>
    
  </subsection>

  <p>
    Chinese mathematicians frequently performed calculations with the aid of a counting board. A counting board consists of columns arranged from right to left in increasing powers of <m>10</m> much as we do today when writing numbers. Numbers on the counting board were expressed using counting rods, which were actual rods made of ivory or bamboo.  By the 3rd century A.D. these numbers were described as being horizontal (Heng) or vertical (Zong) numerals. Horizontal numerals were used for odd powers of 10 (tens, thousands, hundred thousands, ...), while vertical numerals were used for even powers of 10 (units, hundreds, ten thousands, ...). Zero was represented by leaving a column blank. Positive and negative numbers were represented by red and black rods respectively. Negative numbers weren't admitted as solutions but they were used in calculations.
  </p>

  <figure>
      <caption>The Chinese Counting Board Numerals</caption>
      <image source="China.jpg" width="50%">
        <description>Chart showing the rod-numeral system used in ancient Chinese mathematics for representing positive and negative integers. The figure is divided into two sections: Positive Numbers at the top in red and Negative Numbers at the bottom in black.
For each section, numbers from 0 through 9 are displayed. The numeral 0 is labeled “space,” indicating an empty position. Each nonzero number is represented using counting rods arranged either vertically or horizontally. The orientation alternates by place value in traditional use.
For positive numbers, the vertical forms use one to four vertical rods for 1–4, five rods represented by a horizontal top bar with a vertical stem (T-shape), and 6–9 formed by adding one to four additional vertical rods to the T-shape. The horizontal forms use one to four horizontal rods for 1–4, five rods represented by a vertical stem with a horizontal base (upside-down T-shape), and 6–9 formed by adding one to four additional horizontal rods.
The lower half shows the corresponding representations for negative numbers in black. The shapes are identical to those for positive numbers, but the color difference distinguishes negative values from positive values.
The diagram illustrates how ancient Chinese rod numerals encoded both magnitude and sign using rod arrangements and color conventions.
          </description>
      </image>
    </figure>

  <p>
    With counting rods, addition and subtraction can be done by repositioning the rods column by column. Multiplication and division are possible with counting rods as well. Another use of counting rods is solving systems of equations. The first problem of Chapter 8 of <em>The Nine Chapters</em> concerns the prices of three different qualities of grain.  
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    <p>
      Suppose that <m>3</m> bing of top quality millet, <m>2</m> bing of medium quality millet, [and] <m>1</m> bing of low quality millet produce <m>39</m> dou of grain; <m>2</m> bing of top quality millet, <m>3</m> bing of medium quality millet, [and] <m>1</m> bing of low quality millet yield <m>34</m> dou. <m>1</m> bing of top quality millet, <m>2</m> bing of medium quality millet, [and] <m>3</m> bing of low quality millet yield <m>26</m> dou. One asks how much is produced respectively by one of high, medium, and low quality millet.
    </p>
  </blockquote>

  <p>
    We will solve this problem using modern numerals and notation, but we will use the same method from <em>The Nine Chapters</em>. Let <m>x</m>, <m>y</m>, and <m>z</m> represent the top, medium, and low quality millet. Then we can express the equations given in the problem as 
    <md>
      <mrow> 3x+2y+z \amp = 39 </mrow>
      <mrow> 2x+3y+z \amp = 34 </mrow>
      <mrow> x+2y+3z \amp = 26 </mrow>
    </md>
    
  </p>

  <p>
    We next represent these equations using a rectangular array. Chinese mathematicians would have written these numbers from top to bottom and left to right, but we will keep them in the familiar form. To create this array, we record the coefficients of each term.
    <md>
      \left[
\begin{array}{ccc|c}
3 \amp 2 \amp 1 \amp 39\\
2 \amp 3 \amp 1 \amp 34\\
1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 26
\end{array}
\right]
    </md>
    
  </p>

  <p>
    Our goal is to reduce the matrix on the left to an <term>upper triangular matrix</term>. An upper triangular matrix is a matrix in which every entry below the diagonal from top left to bottom right is zero. For example the following is an upper triangular matrix.
    <md>
      \left[
\begin{array}{ccc|c}
3 \amp 2 \amp 1 \amp 39\\
0 \amp 3 \amp 1 \amp 34\\
0 \amp 0 \amp 3 \amp 26
\end{array}
\right]
    </md>
    
  </p>

  <p>
    To reduce the matrix to an upper triangular matrix, we will use the following operations.
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Multiply a row by a non-zero constant
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Add or subtract one row from another
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Switch the position of two rows
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </p>

  <p>
    These are the same operations that we would use to solve an elimination problem with 2 unknowns. Now let's use these operations to solve the problem from <em>The Nine Chapters</em>. There are several ways that this can be done, but we will follow the approach used in <em>The Nine Chapters</em>.
  </p>

  <p>
    The first step is to multiply the middle row by the highest coefficient of <m>x</m> in the top row (<m>3</m>).
     <md>
      \left[
\begin{array}{ccc|c}
3 \amp 2 \amp 1 \amp 39\\
6 \amp 9 \amp 3 \amp 102\\
1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 26
\end{array}
\right]
    </md>
  </p>

  <p>
    Now we subtract the top row from the middle row as many times as needed to eliminate the <m>x</m> position in the middle row.
     <md>
      \left[
\begin{array}{ccc|c}
3 \amp 2 \amp 1 \amp 39\\
0 \amp 5 \amp 1 \amp 24\\
1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 26
\end{array}
\right]
    </md>
  </p>

  <p>
    Now we repeat these operations to eliminate the <m>x</m> entry of the bottom row.

    <md>
      \left[
\begin{array}{ccc|c}
3 \amp 2 \amp 1 \amp 39\\
0 \amp 5 \amp 1 \amp 24\\
3 \amp 6 \amp 9 \amp 78
\end{array}
\right]
    </md>

    <md>
      \left[
\begin{array}{ccc|c}
3 \amp 2 \amp 1 \amp 39\\
0 \amp 5 \amp 1 \amp 24\\
0 \amp 4 \amp 8 \amp 39
\end{array}
\right]
    </md>
  </p>

  <p>
    Next we multiply the bottom row by the highest coefficient in the middle row and repeatedly subtract the middle row to eliminate the <m>y</m> entry of the bottom row.
    <md>
      \left[
\begin{array}{ccc|c}
3 \amp 2 \amp 1 \amp 39\\
0 \amp 5 \amp 1 \amp 24\\
0 \amp 20 \amp 40 \amp 195
\end{array}
\right]
    </md>

    <md>
      \left[
\begin{array}{ccc|c}
3 \amp 2 \amp 1 \amp 39\\
0 \amp 5 \amp 1 \amp 24\\
0 \amp 0 \amp 36 \amp 99
\end{array}
\right]
    </md>
  </p>

  <p>
    Now that we have reduced the matrix into upper-triangular form we can solve for the variables using the process of <term>back substitution</term>. First we turn the matrix back into a system of equations
    <md>
      <mrow> 3x+2y+z \amp = 39 </mrow>
      <mrow> 5y+ 1 \amp = 24 </mrow>
      <mrow> 36z \amp = 99 </mrow>
    </md>
    
  </p>

  <p>
    We can solve the last equation for <m>z</m> to find that <m>z= \frac{99}{36} = 2\frac{3}{4}</m>. Then substituting this value into the middle equation we can solve for <m>y</m> and find that <m>5y + 2\frac{3}{4} = 24</m> which means that <m>y = 4\frac{1}{4}</m>. Substituting both <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> into the top equation gives <m>3x+9\frac{1}{2}+ 2 \frac{3}{4} = 39</m> which implies that <m>x = 9\frac{1}{4}</m>. So the final solution is that top quality millet produces <m>9\frac{1}{4}</m>, medium quality <m>4 \frac{1}{4}</m> and low quality <m>2\frac{3}{4}</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Note that this method avoided using fractions until the very end. This is because working with fractions on a counting board is difficult.
  </p>



  </section>